                tradeConversationPlaceholder(role: "Codex", kind: "US Close", title: "2026-05-07 CF beat but sold off; earnings-catch-up now becomes sell-the-news test", body: "Verdict: Notify / watch closely, still no grain trade. CF reported Q1 2026 net sales of about $1.99B, diluted EPS $3.98, and adjusted EBITDA $983M, confirming that nitrogen pricing is flowing through earnings. But CF closed May 6 down about 6.5% to $119.76, while MOS rose about 1.3% to $23.56 and NTR's after-hours reaction looked negative despite adjusted EPS near consensus. Trade read: Stage 1 fertilizer earnings strength is real, but the market may already be fading peak-margin expectations. Next trigger is the May 7 CF/NTR calls: listen for whether high urea/nitrogen pricing persists beyond spring planting or whether management frames the spike as temporary.")
                tradeConversationPlaceholder(role: "Codex", kind: "US Close", title: "2026-05-06 Planting normal; Stage 2 not triggered", body: "Verdict: Research only / no grain trade. USDA crop progress for the week ending 2026-05-03 shows US corn 38% planted vs 34% five-year average and soybeans 33% planted vs 23% average; emergence is also ahead. Spring wheat is only slightly behind on planting, while winter wheat condition remains the yellow flag at roughly 31% good/excellent. Trade read: planting disruption is not the scare yet. Keep Stage 1 fertilizer/earnings-catch-up and possible urea-demise setups on watch, but do not add WEAT/CORN/DBA unless grains break range and crop/yield stress confirms.")
                tradeConversationPlaceholder(role: "Codex", kind: "Framework", title: "Fertilizer spike vs equity lag", body: "Urea is a commodity, not a company. The +91% urea move means the first fertilizer-price spike is already visible; the investable question is whether CF/NTR/MOS/MOO still have earnings catch-up left or whether a post-planting urea rollover creates the better overshoot/demise trade.")
            }
