            - Proposed final dividend: RMB0.70 per share

            **H2 read:** H1 profit was about RMB1.373B, implying H2 profit around RMB1.17B. The recovery is real versus a weak base, but H2 was softer than H1 and revenue growth remains modest.

            **Analysis:** positive margin repair supports the dividend thesis, but this is recovery income, not a growth breakout.
            """
        case "1234 HK":
            return """
            **Latest reported period:** FY2025. China Lilang does not report US-style quarterly earnings; the closest current-period read is H2 2025 from annual minus H1.

            **FY2025 result:**
            - Revenue: RMB4.07B, +11.5%
            - Profit attributable: RMB502.4M, +9.0%
            - Gross margin: 49.6%, +1.9 percentage points
            - EPS: RMB41.96 cents
            - Dividend: HK13c final + HK3c special final, after HK11c interim + HK5c special interim

            **H2 read:** H1 revenue was RMB1.727B and H1 profit RMB242.5M, implying H2 revenue around RMB2.34B and H2 profit around RMB260M. Top-line momentum improved, but operating margin compression and inventory turnover are the quality checks.

            **Analysis:** attractive cheap-yield screen, but result quality is mixed because revenue growth did not fully translate into operating leverage.
            """
        case "DDOG":
            return """
            **Next clean result catalyst:** Q1 FY2026 earnings on May 7, 2026.

            **Latest known setup:** FY2026 revenue guidance was roughly $4.06B-$4.10B, with Q1 guidance around $951M-$961M. The Q1 print is the first hard check after the SaaS overshoot entry.

            **Result-date note:** Datadog has officially scheduled Q1 FY2026 earnings for May 7, 2026. T+1 / T+2 / T+3 stay Pending until the first three regular US trading sessions after the announcement.

            **What the market will test:** revenue durability, net retention direction, large-customer adds, usage growth, AI-native customer concentration, security/observability attach, and whether cloud optimization pressure is fading.
            """
        case "SNOW":
            return """
            **Latest reported period:** Q4 FY2026 / FY2026, reported February 25, 2026.

            **Key result:** product revenue was $1.23B in Q4, +30% YoY. Remaining performance obligations were $9.77B, +42% YoY. Net revenue retention was 125%, and the company guided FY2027 product revenue to roughly $5.66B, +27% YoY.

            **Next catalyst:** Q1 FY2027 is expected in late May, with Investor Day / Summit week beginning June 1. This makes SNOW the staggered second target after DDOG rather than another May 7 event-risk name.

            **What the market will test:** product revenue durability, NRR stability, RPO growth, AI workload monetization, data-platform consumption, Observe integration, margin discipline, and whether AI features translate into real revenue.
            """
        case "NET":
            return """
            **Next clean result catalyst:** Q1 FY2026 earnings on May 7, 2026 after market close.

            **Current result role:** NET is useful read-through for security, connectivity, edge compute, and AI traffic demand, but it overlaps DDOG's May 7 earnings risk. Do not use it as the second target if DDOG is already the main event-risk position.

            **What the market will test:** revenue growth, large customer additions, dollar-based expansion, security platform traction, Workers / developer platform momentum, AI inference/network commentary, and margin discipline.
            """
        case "TEAM":
            return """
            **Latest reported period:** Q3 FY2026, reported April 30, 2026 after market close.

            **T+1 verdict:** TEAM closed $88.88 on May 1, +29.58% versus the $68.59 pre-result close. That is the cleanest confirmation so far that the market will reward punished SaaS if numbers and guidance are good enough.

            **Trade role:** keep TEAM as the litmus. Do not chase it as the second target unless it sets up again. A strong T+2 / T+3 hold improves confidence in DDOG and SNOW.
            """
        case "PLTR":
            return """
            **Latest reported period:** Q1 2026, reported May 4, 2026 after market close.

            **Q1 result:** revenue was $1.633B, up 85% Y/Y and 16% sequentially. US revenue was $1.282B, up 104% Y/Y. US commercial revenue was $595M, up 133% Y/Y.

            **Profitability:** GAAP EPS was $0.34 and adjusted EPS was $0.33. GAAP operating margin was 46%; adjusted operating margin was 60%. Adjusted free cash flow was $925M, a 57% margin. The balance sheet ended with about $8.0B cash, cash equivalents and US Treasury securities, and no debt.

            **Updated FY2026 guide:** revenue of $7.650B-$7.662B, adjusted operating income of $4.440B-$4.452B, adjusted free cash flow of $4.2B-$4.4B, and US commercial revenue above $3.224B.

            **Market read:** this is a real AI software profit pool, but the post-result stock reaction still matters because valuation is extreme. A great print being sold is a high-expectation warning for the whole AI software basket.
            """
        default:
            return """
            **Latest result:** \(row.resultDate)

            This shared Markdown section should capture:

            - Latest quarter, interim, annual, or macro release
            - Revenue / profit / margin / dividend or equivalent indicator metrics
            - What improved
            - What deteriorated
            - Whether the latest result confirms or weakens the trade thesis
            """
        }
    }

    private func watchResearchNote(for row: NJInvestmentWatchRow) -> String {
        switch row.id {
        case "chinaai-bidu":
            return "Next print must show AI Cloud growth offsetting search-ad drag. Treat as result-risk until Q1 confirms margin quality."
        case "chinaai-baba":
            return "Cloud and AI growth are the core thesis, but quick-commerce spend can compress EBITA. Needs a cleaner margin narrative."
        case "chinaai-tencent":
            return "Beaten-down quality laggard. Q1 must show games, ads, cloud/AI, and margins can hold while AI capex rises and buyback support steps down. Trade plan: 25% starter only before the May 13 result. Add after the announcement only if the stock either holds a good-reaction gap or drops on emotional AI/buyback fear while core fundamentals remain intact."
        case "chinaai-iflytek":
            return "Needs Q1 result read. Watch whether AI model/app investment converts into revenue without fresh margin damage."
        case "chinaai-smic":
            return "China AI scarcity proxy. Upside needs utilization and pricing to offset capex and gross-margin pressure."
        case "chinaai-cambricon":
            return "Purest AI-chip beta in the list, but valuation and liquidity risk are high. Use chart and volume confirmation before sizing."
        case "chinaai-jcet":
            return "Back-end packaging confirmation improved. Watch whether AI/package demand sustains margin and volume after the Q1 print."
        case "chinaai-tongfu":
            return "Packaging beta. Needs confirmation from utilization, customer mix, and margin trend."
        case "chinaai-huatian":
            return "Lower-priced packaging exposure. Needs volume and earnings confirmation before it matters to the AI thesis."
        case "chinaai-usdcnh":
            return "Macro risk reference. If CNH weakens sharply, China AI beta likely needs smaller sizing even when single-name thesis improves."
        default:
            return row.tPlusThree
        }
    }

    private func watchAnalysisMarkdown(for row: NJInvestmentWatchRow) -> String {
        switch row.symbol {
        case "1044 HK":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Hengan is a defensive income recovery candidate, not a growth re-rating story.

            **What is attractive:**
            - Staple repeat-purchase categories
            - FY2025 margin recovery
            - Dividend coverage still looks reasonable
            - Less cyclical than apparel or commodity yield names

            **What stops me from treating it as high quality outright:**
            - Revenue growth is only low-single-digit
            - Tissue competition can quickly reverse margin gains
            - Hygiene categories are not clearly accelerating
            - Debt/cash balance means dividend comfort must come from operating cash flow, not headline cash alone

            **Trade read:** interesting only as a discounted yield name. Prefer buying weakness near technical support or after ex-dividend if price action holds. Avoid chasing if price approaches the 52-week high without stronger revenue growth.
            """
        case "1234 HK":
            return """
            **Current research note:** China Lilang is cheap and high-yielding, but the quality of the yield is lower than telecom / utility / staples yield because apparel is cyclical.

            **What is attractive:**
            - Low valuation
            - High dividend yield
            - Net-cash support
            - FY2025 revenue growth and improved gross margin

            **What keeps it risky:**
            - Special dividends inflate the headline yield
            - Inventory turnover worsened
            - Operating margin did not fully follow revenue growth
            - Mainland discretionary spending can turn quickly

            **Trade read:** only buy at a valuation/risk discount. It can be a high-yield candidate, but it should not be sized like a defensive income stock unless inventory and ordinary-dividend quality improve.
            """
        case "DDOG":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Datadog fits the SaaS overshoot trade because AI/cloud complexity may support usage growth, but the stock needs earnings confirmation.

            **Bull case:** AI workloads increase production complexity, logs, traces, security events, inference latency checks, reliability needs, and model/application monitoring. Datadog's 2026 AI Engineering work points to production AI systems hitting operational problems, which is exactly the type of environment where observability budgets can defend themselves.

            **Bear case:** cloud optimization returns, large-customer concentration distorts growth, and the market refuses to pay for usage-based software without clean broad-based acceleration. The key risk is that AI demand is real but too concentrated, while the rest of the cloud estate grows more slowly.

            **DDOG-specific research checklist:**
            - AI/customer signal: whether AI-native usage is broadening beyond one or two large customers
            - Observability signal: logs, APM, infrastructure monitoring, and incident demand
            - Security signal: cloud security and application security attach rates
            - Efficiency signal: gross margin and FCF discipline while usage grows
            - Guidance signal: whether FY2026 is raised enough to matter, not only met

            **IB Gateway / Monday setup:** Gateway connected on 127.0.0.1:4001 and confirmed May 1 IB bar: close $140.53, high $142.75, low $135.38. Historical bars are usable; live API quotes need additional IB market-data permission.

            **Day-trade levels:** $135-$136 is the first support/entry test. $133.70 is the better reclaim/shakeout entry. $133.60 is the warning line. $129.48 invalidates the pre-earnings test. $142.75 is the upside trigger / Friday high reclaim.

            **Trade rule:** before earnings, starter only. After earnings, beat + stock up means add; beat + flat means cut; beat + down means exit.
            """
        case "SNOW":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Snowflake is the preferred second target because it staggers the SaaS trade away from the DDOG / NET May 7 earnings window while keeping the trade tied to AI/data consumption.

            **Bull case:** enterprises still need governed data platforms to build AI applications, analytics, model workflows, and data engineering pipelines. SNOW's last reported quarter showed product revenue +30%, RPO +42%, NRR 125%, and FY2027 product revenue guidance around +27%, which supports a real data-platform recovery story.

            **Bear case:** SNOW is a consumption model, so product excitement can fail to convert into near-term revenue. AI features may be lower margin, hyperscaler-native data stacks remain competitive, and the stock has not shown the same force as DDOG / NET yet.

            **SNOW-specific research checklist:**
            - Product revenue: Q1 growth versus the 27% guide
            - NRR: whether 125% can hold or improve
            - RPO: whether bookings stay strong outside Q4 seasonality
            - AI signal: real customer spend from Snowflake Intelligence, Cortex, and model partnerships
            - Margin signal: whether AI workload growth pressures product gross margin

            **Trade rule:** starter only near support. Preferred zone is $138-$140 near AVWAP; better risk/reward is $135-$136 if SaaS pulls back and then stabilizes. Do not chase above $145 unless IGV and the whole SaaS basket are breaking out.
            """
        case "NET":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Cloudflare is a good company and a strong software beta, but it is not the preferred second target while DDOG is the primary May 7 test.

            **Bull case:** security, edge networking, developer workloads, and AI traffic can sustain strong demand. NET's price action on May 1 confirmed the SaaS rebound with a +6.11% close.

            **Why it is de-prioritized:** NET reports May 7 after market close while DDOG reports May 7 before market open. Owning both as the main two targets would concentrate the trade in one earnings window. Use NET as read-through unless DDOG is skipped or reduced before the print.

            **IB Gateway / Monday setup:** Gateway confirmed May 1 IB bar: close $217.50, high $218.28, low $209.00. NET remains useful read-through, but live API quotes need additional IB market-data permission.

            **Day-trade levels:** $210-$212 is first support. $207-$210 is the better reclaim zone if the SaaS tape cools. $209 is the warning line because it was Friday's low area. $204.97 invalidates the sympathy bounce. $218.28-$220 is the upside trigger/reclaim zone.

            **Trade rule:** if DDOG is active, NET is confirmation, not target two. If DDOG is skipped, NET can become the tactical substitute only on a clean pullback or post-result confirmation.
            """
        case "TEAM":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Atlassian already performed its job for this trade. It was the seat-based litmus test, and T+1 passed with a +29.58% close after earnings.

            **Bull read-through:** if a seat-sensitive name can be rewarded after clean numbers, usage-based DDOG and data-consumption SNOW deserve serious attention.

            **Why it is not target two:** after the T+1 repricing, TEAM has chase risk. It should validate the thesis, not become the fresh entry unless it gives a new support setup.

            **Trade rule:** watch T+2 and T+3. If TEAM holds the earnings gap, confidence in DDOG and SNOW improves. If TEAM fades the entire gap, reduce aggression across the SaaS basket.
            """
        case "PLTR":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Palantir is the cleanest proof point that AI software can show real revenue, margin and free cash flow now. The problem is not business quality; the problem is how much of that quality is already capitalized.

            **Why it is different from TSLA:** PLTR already has software economics: 46% GAAP operating margin, 60% adjusted operating margin, 57% adjusted free cash flow margin and no debt. TSLA is still mostly a manufacturer trying to persuade the market that FSD, robotaxi, Optimus and AI chips will one day convert the company into a high-margin software/AI platform.

            **Valuation scratch:** around $135.91, PLTR is roughly a $349B company. Against FY2026 revenue guidance near $7.656B, that is about 45-46x FY2026 sales. FY2026 adjusted forward P/E is roughly 100-105x. A FY2027 EPS path near $1.83 would still leave future P/E around 70-75x.

            **Bull case:** AIP is turning into real enterprise deployment, US commercial growth is explosive, government remains strong, margins are already exceptional, and the company has no balance-sheet stress. If investors want profitable AI software instead of capex-heavy AI infrastructure, PLTR is the obvious magnet.

            **Bear case:** at this valuation, even exceptional numbers may not be enough. The stock is priced for many quarters of continued acceleration, high retention, high margins and broad AI adoption. A deceleration from 85% revenue growth or any hint of contract quality weakness can compress the multiple fast.

            **Trade read:** PLTR is a chase candidate only if price action confirms momentum after the earnings digestion. It is not a cheap stock. It is a high-quality, high-expectation AI software momentum trade.
            """
        case "0700 HK":
            return """
            **Current research note:** Tencent is a cheap-quality-under-pressure setup, not a confirmed turnaround yet.

            **Pre-result plan:** only a 25% starter before the May 13, 2026 Q1 result. Do not move to 50% before the print unless the market clearly stabilizes and reclaims the prior danger zone.

            **If the result is good and the stock gaps up:** do not chase the first spike blindly. Add only if it holds the gap, ideally reclaiming the HK$480-490 area with volume and no immediate fade.

            **If the result disappoints and the stock drops:** do not automatically buy the drop. Add only if the disappointment is mostly about near-term AI spend / lower buyback anxiety while games, ads, fintech, cloud, and margins remain solid.

            **What would block adding:** core business weakness, clear margin compression, management signaling materially lower buybacks with no AI monetization path, or a heavy-volume break below the fresh HK$463-460 support zone.

            **Sizing path:** 25% starter now / next week, add 25% only after evidence, and reserve 75-100% sizing for confirmation that business quality and capital allocation fears are overdone.
            """
        case "0005 HK":
            return """
            **Current research note:** HSBC is a dividend parking-lot candidate, not an attractive MFS buy at the current yield.

            **MFS rule:** prefer Chinese SOE banks over HSBC unless 0005 falls below HK$120. Below HK$120, re-check yield, CET1, ECL trend, and buyback language before acting.

            **Why HK$120 matters:** using FY2025 total DPS of US$0.75/share, HK$120 implies roughly a 4.9% yield before any dividend growth. That is only where the name starts to become worth reviewing again; it is not an automatic buy.

            **Current read:** Q1 2026 kept the dividend alive, but the report did not improve the capital-return story. CET1 is at the bottom of management's 14.0%-14.5% target range, ECL guidance moved up, and buybacks remain subject to quarterly review.

            **Action rule:** above HK$120, watch only and rank behind ICBC / CCB / BOC / ABC for income parking. Below HK$120, reassess for parking-lot sizing. The more attractive zone remains closer to HK$100 if the dividend remains intact.
            """
        case "0941 HK":
            return """
            **Current research note:** China Mobile is a defensive yield compounder that may become an actionable buy if tech-led rotation pushes the stock down too far relative to its cash-return quality.

            **What is attractive:**
            - Around 6%+ dividend yield with a June 2026 ex-dividend window
            - Stronger balance sheet and cash generation than the other big China telcos
            - Defensive operating model with cloud/AI optionality, even if the market does not pay for it like a growth name
            - Rotation out of defensives can create better entry levels without changing the core thesis

            **What keeps it from being a simple buy:**
            - Q1 2026 was soft rather than exciting, with profit down year over year
            - The market still sees it as a mature telecom, not a rerating AI name
            - If the whole defensive bucket is being funded for risk-on trades, valuation support can take time to matter

            **Trade read:** treat HK$82 as the preferred entry target on rotation-driven weakness. If that zone holds and the tape still looks like rotation rather than a fundamental break, the first recovery target is HK$88.50, with a stretch retest toward HK$90.00-90.60. If the dividend is collected later, the effective basis moves closer to the HK$79.50 deep-value zone.
            """
        default:
            return """
            **Research note for \(row.symbol) / \(row.name)**

            Use this tab as the living analysis note for the symbol. Capture:

            - Current thesis
            - Why it belongs in this watchlist
            - What has changed since it was added
            - Price/chart read
            - Key catalyst
            - What would make us add, hold, cut, or remove it

            **Current watch read:** \(watchResearchNote(for: row))
            """
        }
    }

    private func watchRiskMarkdown(for row: NJInvestmentWatchRow) -> String {
        switch row.symbol {
        case "1044 HK":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** Hengan is a defensive yield recovery candidate, but margin durability is the key risk.

            **Main risks:**
            - Tissue price competition returns and compresses gross margin
            - Raw-material costs rise faster than pricing power
            - Hygiene-product weakness offsets tissue recovery
            - Large cash balance is offset by meaningful debt, so operating cash flow still matters
            - Payout ratio rises materially above the low-60s area

            **Invalidation:** cut or avoid if margin recovery stalls, debt/cash comfort worsens, or the stock rallies near the 52-week high while revenue growth remains only low-single-digit.
            """
        case "1234 HK":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** China Lilang is a cheap high-yield apparel stock, but the yield is cyclical and partly special-dividend dependent.

            **Main risks:**
            - Mainland menswear demand weakens
            - Inventory turnover days keep rising
            - Channel/distributor pressure forces discounts or support
            - Special dividend is cut, exposing the ordinary yield as less attractive
            - Revenue growth comes with weaker operating margin

            **Invalidation:** avoid if inventory worsens, same-store/channel signals deteriorate, or dividend yield no longer compensates for apparel cyclicality versus cash and higher-quality HK yield names.
            """
        case "DDOG":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** strong platform, but the stock is sensitive to usage growth, cloud optimization, AI-customer concentration, and earnings reaction.

            **Chart / AVWAP read:** May 1 close was $140.53 versus Apr 24 anchored VWAP near $133.43. Above AVWAP, DDOG is still acting constructively. A clean loss of AVWAP shifts the test back toward risk-control mode.

            **Support zones:** $135-$136 first pullback support, then $133.70 reclaim/shakeout entry, then $133.60 warning. The $129.48 starter reference is the hard pre-earnings invalidation.

            **Resistance zones:** $142.75 Friday high / trigger line, then $145 as the next chase-risk area. A push through this band before May 7 would mean the market is starting to pre-price a good result.

            **Main risks:**
            - Usage growth slows
            - Large AI-native customer concentration distorts growth quality
            - Cloud optimization pressure returns
            - Earnings beat is sold or guidance is not enough

            **Decision rule:** beat + stock up means add; beat + flat means cut; beat + down means exit. For the pre-result test, keep risk anchored to AVWAP and the $129.48 starter reference.
            """
        case "0005 HK":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** HSBC is still well-capitalized, but there is not enough surplus capital cushion to make the buyback story strong right now.

            **Capital risk:** CET1 is 14.0%, which is the bottom of HSBC's 14.0%-14.5% management target range. Every 0.5 percentage point of CET1 is roughly US$4.4bn on current RWAs, so rebuilding capital can compete with buybacks.

            **Credit risk:** ECL guidance rose from around 40bps to around 45bps for 2026. That does not break the bank, but it tells the market credit quality is now the thing to watch.

            **Dividend risk:** Q1 declared US$0.10/share, but the yield is not attractive enough above HK$120. At current higher prices, HSBC is not giving enough income compensation for CET1/ECL uncertainty, especially versus Chinese SOE bank alternatives.

            **Invalidation / action:** do not use for MFS above HK$120. Prefer Chinese banks for the same income bucket unless HSBC reprices. Re-open below HK$120 only if credit quality is controlled and management does not further weaken the capital-return path.
            """
        case "SNOW":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** Snowflake is the staggered second target, but it is a consumption-model trade. Price must confirm that AI/data excitement is turning into durable usage and not only product narrative.

            **Chart / AVWAP read:** May 1 close was $141.00 versus Apr 24 anchored VWAP near $140.34. That is constructive but not forceful. SNOW needs to hold the $138-$140 area or reclaim it quickly after any dip.

            **Support zones:** $138-$140 first support and AVWAP zone, then $135-$136 as the better risk/reward pullback area. A sustained break below $133 means the SaaS catch-up leg is failing.

            **Resistance zones:** $144-$145 is the first area where chase risk rises. Above that, require IGV and the broader SaaS basket to confirm before adding.

            **Main risks:**
            - Product revenue growth slows below the guide
            - NRR weakens from the 125% area
            - AI product adoption does not convert into paid consumption
            - AI workloads pressure product gross margin
            - Hyperscaler-native data and AI stacks compress the platform premium

            **Decision rule:** SNOW is target two only if it holds support. Do not chase it just because DDOG works. The purpose is staggered exposure with better timing, not extra beta at any price.
            """
        case "NET":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** Cloudflare can work, but using NET alongside DDOG concentrates event risk because both report on May 7.

            **Chart / AVWAP read:** May 1 close was $217.50 versus Apr 24 anchored VWAP near $209.86. The chart improved, but it is already a strong sympathy move ahead of earnings.

            **Support zones:** $210-$212 first support, then $207-$210 better reclaim zone. $209 is the warning line because it was Friday's low area. $204.97 invalidates the sympathy bounce.

            **Resistance zones:** $218.28-$220 is the trigger/reclaim band. Do not chase above it unless DDOG, TEAM and IGV also confirm.

            **Main risks:**
            - Same-window event risk with DDOG
            - A high bar into earnings after the May 1 rebound
            - Security / edge / developer platform demand is good but already priced
            - A good print is sold because expectations reset too quickly

            **Decision rule:** use NET as read-through while DDOG is the primary May 7 test. Only promote NET to an active target if DDOG is skipped, reduced, or invalidated before earnings.
            """
        case "TEAM":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** TEAM validated the trade, but after a +29.58% T+1 move it carries chase and gap-fade risk.

            **What matters now:** T+2 and T+3 should defend the earnings gap. If TEAM gives back too much of the move, the SaaS overshoot thesis weakens because the first clean proof point failed to hold.

            **Main risks:**
            - The market treats the T+1 move as a one-day short squeeze
            - Seat-based demand optimism fades
            - Software ETF strength does not continue
            - Investors rotate back out of SaaS before DDOG reports

            **Decision rule:** do not use TEAM as the fresh second target after the gap. Use it as the tape judge for DDOG and SNOW.
            """
        case "PLTR":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** PLTR is already delivering high-margin AI software economics, but the stock has very little room for merely good news.

            **Valuation risk:** around $135.91, PLTR screens near 45-46x FY2026 sales and roughly 100-105x FY2026 adjusted earnings. That means the market is not paying for normal software; it is paying for sustained AI platform dominance.

            **Expectation risk:** Q1 revenue growth was 85% Y/Y and US commercial growth was 133% Y/Y. Those numbers are excellent, but they set a brutal comparison base. Any slowdown can be treated as thesis damage even if the absolute business remains strong.

            **Reaction risk:** the stock sold after a strong print. That does not prove the thesis is broken, but it proves the bar is high. Great AI software numbers are no longer automatically enough.

            **TSLA comparison risk:** PLTR's margin is real today, while TSLA's high-margin story is still optionality. That makes PLTR a cleaner quality chase, but it also means there is less hidden-margin upside left to discover.

            **Decision rule:** chase only on confirmed price strength. If the stock cannot reclaim the post-earnings damage quickly, treat it as a sector warning for DDOG, SNOW and the broader AI software basket.
            """
        case "0700 HK":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** Tencent can still drop further before or after May 13 because the market is pricing lower buyback support, higher AI spend, Prosus selling overhang, and uncertainty around AI monetization.

            **Support / control zone:** HK$463-460 is the current danger zone after the latest selloff. A heavy-volume break below this area means do not add.

            **Main risks:**
            - 2026 buybacks are meaningfully lower than 2025
            - AI investment rises faster than visible AI revenue
            - Prosus selling continues to cap rallies
            - Q1 result shows weakness in games, ads, fintech, cloud, or margin quality
            - A good result is sold, which would mean capital-allocation fear still dominates valuation

            **Decision rule:** starter before result is acceptable, but the main add decision waits for the May 13 reaction. Chase only if the gap holds; buy the dip only if the dip is emotional rather than fundamental.
            """
        case "0941 HK":
            return """
            **Risk summary:** China Mobile can still drift lower if the market keeps using defensives as a funding source, even if the dividend and balance-sheet story stays intact.

            **Support / control zone:** HK$82 is the preferred target/entry zone on the medium-term chart. A clean break that cannot reclaim HK$81 means stop assuming this is only a rotation overshoot and be prepared to wait closer to the HK$79.50 dividend-adjusted value zone.

            **Resistance zones:** HK$85.30 is the first reclaim line, then HK$86.80-87.20 is the first real upside supply area. If the stock clears that band cleanly, HK$88.50 becomes the working first target, with HK$90.00-90.60 as the stretch retest zone.

            **Main risks:**
            - Q1 softness in core business revenue turns into a longer de-rating
            - Defensive yield names remain out of favor while tech leadership stays dominant
            - Cloud/AI monetization fails to offset mature telecom perceptions
            - The stock weakens even into the June dividend window, which would suggest more than simple rotation pressure

            **Decision rule:** add only if price weakness looks rotational and support begins to hold. Do not average down aggressively through HK$82.20 unless the business thesis clearly improved.
            """
        default:
            return """
            **Risk summary:** \(watchResearchNote(for: row))

            This shared Markdown section should capture:

            - Fundamental risk
            - Valuation risk
            - Balance sheet / dividend / result-quality risk
            - Technical risk from the chart
            - Exact invalidation trigger
            """
        }
    }

    private var henganResearchPanel: some View {
        VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 12) {
            researchCard(title: "Business Quality", status: "Stable staples") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("Hengan is a China household and hygiene-products compounder: tissue paper is the growth stabilizer, while hygiene products are the slower / more competitive leg.")
                    Text("FY2025 was good enough for an income watch: revenue rose 1.8%, gross margin improved to 33.8% from 32.3%, and profit attributable to shareholders rose 10.3%. This is quality income, but not a fast-growth story.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Dividend Quality", status: "Good cover") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("Dividend looks serviceable rather than stretched: annual dividend around HK$1.61, yield about 6%, payout ratio around 63%, and semiannual pattern still intact.")
                    Text("The proposed FY2025 final dividend is RMB0.70 per share, matching the RMB0.70 interim dividend. Next key cut-off to watch is the May 2026 ex-dividend window.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Latest Result", status: "FY2025 / H2 read") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("Hengan does not report US-style quarterly earnings. Latest full filing is FY2025; the closest current-period read is H2 2025 after comparing annual results with the H1 2025 interim.")
                    Text("FY2025: revenue RMB23.07B, up 1.8%; net profit attributable to shareholders RMB2.54B, up 10.3%; gross margin improved to 33.8%. Final dividend proposed at RMB0.70 per share.")
                    Text("H2 read: H1 profit was about RMB1.373B, so H2 profit was roughly RMB1.17B. That implies the second half recovered versus the weak 2024 base, but was softer than H1. Revenue momentum is still modest, not explosive.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Result Analysis", status: "Recovery, not breakout") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("Positive: tissue paper growth and cost/product-mix improvement repaired margins enough to support the dividend thesis.")
                    Text("Negative: the recovery is not broad. Hygiene-product sales remain weaker, promotions are still a pressure point, and management expects operating pressure to persist in 2026.")
                    Text("Investment read: buy only as a defensive income recovery. Do not value it like a growth compounder unless revenue growth and category mix both improve.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Latest News", status: "Mar 2026") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("FY2025 results were better on the surface: net profit rose 10.3% after gross margin improved, helped by product mix and cost control.")
                    Text("The warning underneath: revenue only grew 1.8%, tissue competition is still intense, and management still talks about operating pressure. This is a yield recovery story, not a clean growth story.")
                    Text("Relevant prior bad news: in 1H2025 profit fell around 35% as tissue price competition and raw-material pressure hit margins. The newest rebound matters because it shows recovery, but it does not erase the cycle risk.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Risk Analysis", status: "Margin + balance sheet") {
                VStack(alignment: .leading, spacing: 8) {
                    Text("Main risk is margin mean reversion: if tissue prices weaken again or input costs rise, the 33.8% gross margin can fade and the dividend stops looking defensive.")
                    Text("Second risk is balance-sheet optics: cash is large, but debt is also large, so the dividend needs operating cash flow support rather than just cash-on-hand comfort.")
                    Text("Third risk is weak category mix: hygiene products are slower and more competitive, so tissue has to carry the income thesis. If tissue volume or pricing stalls, this becomes a value trap.")
                }
            }

            researchCard(title: "Decision Rule", status: "Income watch") {
                Text("Prefer below/near mid-cycle valuation, do not chase after ex-dividend. Add only if live yield stays attractive and price is not already near the 52-week high; cut if margin recovery stalls, debt/cash gap worsens, or payout ratio moves materially above the current low-60s area.")
            }

            researchCard(title: "Sources", status: "Latest checked") {
                Text("HKEX FY2025 annual results announcement, 17 Mar 2026; H1 2025 interim result notes; The Standard result note, 18 Mar 2026; StockAnalysis 1044 dividend/statistics pages, checked Apr 2026.")
                    .font(.caption)
            }
        }
    }

